omg! woke up to the news today that i was longlisted for the Carol Shields Prize for Fiction 💗💗💗 i’m so honored and i adore this list! also here’s a random photo of me being a hot-they for the algorithm 💗
YALL!! i am so honored to be named on the @carolshieldsprize shortlist alongside these amazing authors and to also be named the best new novel by @chicago_reader !!! i’m besides myself with joy 💗
lately 💕

i really truly have no words after yesterday. being longlisted for the inaugural carol shields prize was such an honor, let alone being able to be in tennessee with the other finalists and then winning. 

the whole night i was so emotional— hearing Susan Swan talk about the 12 year creation process for this award, hearing Ann Patchett talk about meeting Carol Shield and the longevity of writing, hearing Margaret Atwood talk about witnessing the creation of this award and her own experience with prizes. and then hearing all of the jury so lovingly talk about each other finalists work made me tear up. i’m so grateful for each of the jury members: katherena vermette, crystal wilkinson, anita rau badami, merilyn simonds and monique truong 💗 and for my other finalists: daphne palasi andreades, talia lakshmi jollities, suzette mayr and alexis schaitkin!!

i’m so grateful to everyone who made this prize possible 💞

there were so many moments where i thought i couldn’t finish this book. i’m so so so in gratitude to Allah, great creator & to my ancestors and guides for being so loving with me through this process. and for all my friends and community who held me down each step of the way. for everyone who offered words of encouragement in the darkness, who believed in me, who made this possible. for all the writers who have shaped me. for all my teachers. and for everyone who has read this book, thank you. 💗🧿

i’ve always been so struck by the tender love between franny and cam, the slow care, the noticing that occurs between the two of them. how they saw each other and said, yes, that one, then chose to rise into that love, to be worthy of that love, to grow into that love. this weekend was incredible, one that i don’t fully have the words for, but will sit with for a long time— one of my best friends got married to a friend i adore. oh franny, i’ve seen you grieve loss and love and pray for a place for your heart to be safe enough to rest. oh franny, i’ve seen you love harder and more generously than i thought possible. oh cam, i’ve hidden under blankets with you tucked in a corner of the room while a party rages around us. oh cam, i’ve heard you speak and seen it melt a room. oh cam, i’ve seen you answer franny’s prayer. my friends found each other. my friends fell in love. my friends chose to share and celebrate that love with us. my friends chose to build a life of love together. that’s the greatest ameeen that could ever exist 💗

we all benefit so much from people of color, queer people and other marginalized folks sharing art. art has the incredible power to transcend boundaries, connect cultures, and ignite change. I have been horrified to see the wave of censorship and book bans sweeping the country in recent months— i don’t want to live in a world that censures marginalized peoples art. i’m signing my name to the #ArtistsAgainstBookBans open letter. as artists, we must band together because a threat to one form of art is a threat to us all. Join me and @MoveOn in the movement to stand up against the restriction of artistic expression and literature: ArtistsAgainstBookBans.com #ReadBannedBooks

may allah cover palestine. today, tomorrow, forever. 💗

(shared with me by my beloved friend @cecime.seed )

prayers for everyone in palestine and afghanistan and the entire palestinian and afghan diasporas. 

the children, the women, the men, the trans and queer and non-binary folks. the people who usually don’t count or are villanized in statistics. there is so much propaganda out right now, all attempting to justify the unjustifiable— the genocide  that has been unfolding in front of us since the late 1940s in palestine. currently, the government of israel is enacting indiscriminate bombings campaigns against palestinians and blocking humanitarian aid, which is a war crime.

prayers to afghanistan that has experienced its fourth earthquake in a week and has been the subject of US violence and bombing campaigns for decades.

on tuesday night i was able to visit @insurreallife with @sheer_awe and talk to students. i’m so glad we had a space to talk about writing and also hold space together in such a trying time. one of the questions was about people wanting to write poems in solidarity with other groups, but feeling fear that it wasn’t their place because of not having that lived experience or being from those communities. this is part of my answer, and also saying that we have to stand in our own positionally and write from that place as we cultivate our solidarity. and not being afraid to admit when we’re wrong, and to apologize, to admit it quickly and correct our behavior, because that’s what allows us to grow and evolve and learn more. 

of course that’s not it or enough— with everything unfolding in palestine and the extreme censorship we have to do all we can— donate, protest, call our government and demand a ceasefire, and an end to the genocide and apartheid. but as writers, we also must write in the ways we can— the call from folks on the ground is to be as loud as possible, to keep talking about it, to make sure we’re talking an amplifying to break through the repression of our governments. 

may allah cover palestine, and all of the places in the world where state violence and climate change is upending the lives of humans who want nothing more to than just live in peace— sudan, kashmir, afghanistan, haiti, and so many more.
call call call. call as many days as you can.  it’s so easy. thank you @jewishvoiceforpeace for making this so easy for us 💗
within our lifetime.

“We are citizens of the most powerful country in the world, a country which stands upon the wrong side of every liberation struggle on earth.” — Audre Lorde

thank you @nouraerakat for sharing this.

first two are for the algorithm. please read this article by @rhm.nm  every person behind the statistics of 7,000 murdered in palestine has a face, a name, a personality, a story. please please remember this. please call for a ceasefire and end to israeli occupation. please.

we are in the middle of an enormous human rights crisis, from the genocide across palestine (both the west bank and gaza— especially right now with Susiya and Masafer Yatta, where palestinians deserve to stay on their land), to the occupation of kashmir by both indian and pakistani governments, to the pakistan governments forced return of afghan refugees in 48 hours, to the genocides happening in the congo and sudan. it’s overwhelming, how much is ongoing right now. i know how deeply linked all of these struggles are. people are, and have always been, more important than the governing bodies that dictate what is possible for them. all of our fights are simultaneous, intersecting, and deeply critical. i believe in a world where we are all liberated and where none of our liberation comes at the expense of anyone else’s, where we see how critical it is for all of us to be free in order for freedom to exist fully. here are some action steps: 1. raise awareness for all these causes; 2. call for an immediate ceasefire and end to israeli occupation of palestine; 3. donate to the Palestinian Children’s Relief Fund, the Sudan Relief Mazin Fund— if anyone has funds that directly help the congo and afghan refugees in pakistan pls let me know and i will update; 4. protest; 5. have as many conversations as you can with people in person to raise awareness

this interview is so important and so powerful. i’m so grateful for this nurses testimony. i also see the way that CNN continually tries to ask questions that put the blame on palestinian people who are surviving genocide. this is symbolic of the ways that CNN has had uneven and biased reporting against Palestinian people. please watch this. this nurses testimony on the resources in the refugee camps and the injuries is heartbreaking. the people in gaza who are staying behind while they’re being bombed are heroes. so are the people who are able to leave gaza and try and escape. my heart is with the people who are trying to protect themselves, their families and their communities.

free ahed tamimi 💗

IN SOLIDARITY WITH ONE WORLD AUTHOR AHED TAMIMI

As a coalition of authors published by One World, we stand in solidarity with Palestinian writer and activist Ahed Tamimi, who was imprisoned by the Israeli Defense Forces on November 6, 2023 during a raid on her village, Nabi Saleh, in the West Bank. We call on President Biden to demand Ahed Tamimi’s immediate release; to cease the U.S.-backed genocide of Palestinians in Gaza; and to demand a stop to the IDF raids on Palestinian villages in the occupied West Bank. 

One World’s mission is to “provide a home for authors who challenge the status quo, subvert dominant narratives, and give us new language to understand our past, present, and future.” Ahed Tamimi is the embodiment of this ethos. She is a world-renowned leader in the Palestinian liberation movement. Her memoir, They Called Me a Lioness: A Palestinian Girl’s Fight for Freedom, published by One World in 2022, recounts her imprisonment at 16 years old in December 2017, after she was filmed slapping an IDF soldier who shot her cousin in the head at close range with a rubber-coated bullet. 

We stand with Ahed Tamimi and insist on her immediate return to safety. We stand by her right to write and speak freely, without censure or persecution, about the struggle of Palestinian people and her fight for liberation. 

In the days leading up to her arrest, Tamimi’s family reported that she was part of an online smear campaign created by settlers. Her social media being hacked is a regular occurrence for her. 

Free Ahed Tamimi. Free Palestine.

on Oct 24 i wrote a piece for a major gay/ queer media outlet about palestine and why queer people needed to show up to palestine. the media company then lost over seven figures of funding due to their pro-palestinian coverage and refused to print my piece. i’ve been so disgusted and outraged at the amount of silencing that’s occurring against writers who are standing up in the face of a genocide. today @autostraddle reprinted my piece, being one of the only queer outlets who is willing to take a pro-palestinian stance. queer people: the pink washing in our communities MUST stop. we must combat it at every turn. we must. who are we if we don’t?

here are some excerpts from my piece, but you can read the full thing on my substack or at autostraddle.
for freedom 💗

today is my little baby yarrows first birthday!! i remember when we first got him and he was so little i had to teach him how to walk on a leash by practicing with him in the hallway. he was so nervous and wouldn’t do it with anyone else and i made up a little song for him and would dance so slowly near him so he would walk 💗 now my baby is all grown up 🥲 thank you for bringing so much joy and play into my life, and like the meaning of your name, helping to heal so many of my frayed edges, helping walk with me as i go further into this life and myself, helping remind me of the joy of the present moment. i love you 💞 🪬
